The Lagos State Local Government Service Commission has warned council workers against unethical conducts or face the law. Chairman of the commission Kamal Bayewu, during a visit to Onigbongbo Local Council Development Area, admonished the workers on the need for discipline and respect for service ethics and decorum. Bayewu, who noted that these sterling qualities had been dwindling in council, called for a return to a productive, forward-looking, and disciplined service.   ‘Tinubu can handle Nigeria’s complexities‘     Lagos trains council officers in registry management     Makinde denies unfairness to Muslims   According to him, some unwholesome activities like the ghost worker syndrome and staff aiding criminal acts must end. He said the commission would not condone such acts and ordered a verification exercise for both junior and senior staff. The Commission’s Permanent Secretary, Abiodun Bamgboye, promised severe punishment to any worker found wanting. According to him, over 55 workers across the state are currently facing disciplinary action. The commission, he said, would weed out bad eggs and criminal elements from the system. Permanent Secretary in the Establishment Training and Pension Office Mrs. Kikelomo Bolarinwa said lack of synergy among the management staff was hindering service delivery. She highlighted the importance of the newly-created Information Communication Technology (ICT) unit, and directed that the office be given all it needs to perform.